- They must be so hungry.

1206
00:39:57,362 --> 00:39:59,461
If it's your turn that day,

1207
00:39:59,462 --> 00:40:01,161
you'd eat like crazy.

1208
00:40:01,162 --> 00:40:02,292
It's my turn today.

1209
00:40:02,492 --> 00:40:03,862
I'm eating jjajangmyeon today.

1210
00:40:04,502 --> 00:40:05,861
Look, Sang Hyun.

1211
00:40:05,862 --> 00:40:07,671
He doesn't just eat food.

1212
00:40:07,672 --> 00:40:10,232
- He'd sometimes drink alcohol.
- Of course.

1213
00:40:10,372 --> 00:40:12,071
Then, does the food taster taste that alcohol as well?

1214
00:40:12,072 --> 00:40:13,742
The only occupations in Korea...

1215
00:40:13,842 --> 00:40:17,082
in which alcohol consumption is permitted while working...

1216
00:40:17,742 --> 00:40:19,582
are the President's food taster...

1217
00:40:19,942 --> 00:40:21,951
and professional alcohol tasters.

1218
00:40:21,952 --> 00:40:23,551
- Right.
- If you want to make it clear,

1219
00:40:23,552 --> 00:40:25,822
say you have the President in front of you,

1220
00:40:26,152 --> 00:40:27,221
do you go near him and say, "I'll open the bottle,"

1221
00:40:27,222 --> 00:40:29,451
and let him hear the sound of it?

1222
00:40:29,452 --> 00:40:30,622
No.

1223
00:40:30,722 --> 00:40:32,421
- An opened one might be doubtful.
- The President...

1224
00:40:32,422 --> 00:40:34,391
- To check if it's fake or not?
- Yes. To check whether it's fake.

1225
00:40:34,392 --> 00:40:36,932
The President authorized...

1226
00:40:37,532 --> 00:40:40,232
the Security Office to be in charge of his safety.

1227
00:40:40,672 --> 00:40:42,402
So the bottle isn't opened in front of the President.

1228
00:40:42,502 --> 00:40:44,371
When the opened bottle comes in, he already knows...

1229
00:40:44,372 --> 00:40:46,572
- He already knows.
- that it was tasted...

1230
00:40:46,942 --> 00:40:48,372
before it came to him.

1231
00:40:48,872 --> 00:40:50,041
An unopened bottle would be more suspicious.

1232
00:40:50,042 --> 00:40:51,212
- You'd know by the sound of it.
- That's right.

1233
00:40:51,682 --> 00:40:53,342
That's how he drinks it.

1234
00:40:53,512 --> 00:40:54,611
There's this thing, though.

1235
00:40:54,612 --> 00:40:57,322
Once people find out what water brand...

1236
00:40:57,782 --> 00:40:59,452
enters the Blue House,

1237
00:40:59,722 --> 00:41:01,752
the brand can no longer supply it from the next day.

1238
00:41:02,592 --> 00:41:04,491
- It has to be kept a secret.
- A top secret.

1239
00:41:04,492 --> 00:41:06,662
- It shouldn't be exposed.
- Right. That shouldn't be known.

1240
00:41:06,892 --> 00:41:08,892
There were people who gave you strawberries and said,

1241
00:41:09,232 --> 00:41:11,062
"These strawberries are supplied to the Blue House."

1242
00:41:11,202 --> 00:41:12,561
- Haven't you heard of that?
- That's right.

1243
00:41:12,562 --> 00:41:13,701
I heard that many times.

1244
00:41:13,702 --> 00:41:15,001
It doesn't matter if they talk among themselves.

1245
00:41:15,002 --> 00:41:16,601
But if that is heard...

1246
00:41:16,602 --> 00:41:18,202
- By someone.
- by someone in the Blue House,

1247
00:41:18,942 --> 00:41:20,711
-You'd have to be careful.
- you'd be investigated...

1248
00:41:20,712 --> 00:41:22,171
- Right.
- You shouldn't talk.

1249
00:41:22,172 --> 00:41:24,842
What are the foods that the presidents so far liked?

1250
00:41:25,042 --> 00:41:28,352
Most of the presidents liked Chinese food.

1251
00:41:28,512 --> 00:41:31,052
For example, white jjamppong, and Yu Xiang eggplant.

1252
00:41:31,322 --> 00:41:32,482
They liked such dishes.

1253
00:41:33,252 --> 00:41:34,621
When President Kim Dae Jung was ill...

1254
00:41:34,622 --> 00:41:36,022
and admitted to Severance Hospital,

1255
00:41:36,322 --> 00:41:38,691
the First Lady asked me...

1256
00:41:38,692 --> 00:41:40,192
to make fotiaoqiang.

1257
00:41:40,792 --> 00:41:43,131
The fotiaoqiang of S Hotel was very famous.

1258
00:41:43,132 --> 00:41:44,601
- I also worked there.
- Chef Hou Deok Juk.

1259
00:41:44,602 --> 00:41:48,402
I made Master Hou Deok Juk's fotiaoqiang...

1260
00:41:49,032 --> 00:41:50,671
and visited him in the hospital...

1261
00:41:50,672 --> 00:41:53,872
with it through the Secretary.

1262
00:41:54,342 --> 00:41:57,012
So the fotiaoqiang was very popular.

1263
00:41:57,482 --> 00:41:59,541
After Sang Hyun's career history,

1264
00:41:59,542 --> 00:42:01,351
- now it's Na Ra.
- Yes.

1265
00:42:01,352 --> 00:42:02,381
- Na Ra.
- Na Ra.

1266
00:42:02,382 --> 00:42:03,411
You wrote "modern-day tavern hostess."

1267
00:42:03,412 --> 00:42:04,451
I'm curious.

1268
00:42:04,452 --> 00:42:05,821
It says you weren't originally...

1269
00:42:05,822 --> 00:42:07,791
- trained as a chef. Right.
- I wasn't.

1270
00:42:07,792 --> 00:42:08,891
I graduated Seoul Institute of the Arts.

1271
00:42:08,892 --> 00:42:10,691
- I majored in film there.
- You studied film?

1272
00:42:10,692 --> 00:42:12,021
Did you study at the Seoul Institute of the Arts?

1273
00:42:12,022 --> 00:42:13,221
- You're my junior.
- Sang Min?

1274
00:42:13,222 --> 00:42:15,362
- You didn't even graduate.
- He didn't graduate.

1275
00:42:15,632 --> 00:42:17,031
- His admission...
- You're a high school graduate.

1276
00:42:17,032 --> 00:42:18,232
- Why do you keep saying that?
- His admission...

1277
00:42:18,432 --> 00:42:20,061
I'm not a high school graduate. I withdrew from university.

1278
00:42:20,062 --> 00:42:22,032
- His admission...
- Who did you know...

1279
00:42:22,302 --> 00:42:24,071
at the Seoul Institute of the Arts?

1280
00:42:24,072 --> 00:42:26,601
My friends in the film major...

1281
00:42:26,602 --> 00:42:28,471
mostly work in theatre.

1282
00:42:28,472 --> 00:42:30,942
People I know from other classes are Dong Hwi...

1283
00:42:31,082 --> 00:42:34,111
Kwun Hyuk Soo, Lee Si Eon, and musical actress Cha Ji Yeon.

1284
00:42:34,112 --> 00:42:35,511
- We studied together.
- There are many of them.

1285
00:42:35,512 --> 00:42:37,751
In the Department of Applied Music...

1286
00:42:37,752 --> 00:42:39,181
- Was there a Department of Ssireum?
- Yes. Applied Music.

1287
00:42:39,182 --> 00:42:40,351
- Ssireum?
- Ssireum?

1288
00:42:40,352 --> 00:42:41,821
It's not the Department of Ssireum.

1289
00:42:41,822 --> 00:42:43,122
- Department of Ssireum...
- Department of Ssireum.

1290
00:42:43,422 --> 00:42:45,091
would have Kang Ho Dong as the professor.

1291
00:42:45,092 --> 00:42:47,061
- I heard the Department of Ssireum.
- I also heard it like that.

1292
00:42:47,062 --> 00:42:48,532
You also heard it like that, right?

1293
00:42:48,632 --> 00:42:50,461
- Yes. I also heard it like that.
- He's even right next to her.

1294
00:42:50,462 --> 00:42:52,032
Professor Kang Ho Dong of the Department of Ssireum.

1295
00:42:52,902 --> 00:42:55,302
How did you switch to traditional liquor from film?

1296
00:42:55,432 --> 00:42:56,971
Did you fall in love with liquor at the retreat?

1297
00:42:56,972 --> 00:42:58,201
I...

1298
00:42:58,202 --> 00:43:00,341
- Drink!
- While shaking your shoulders.

1299
00:43:00,342 --> 00:43:02,841
That's right. You start with the mask dance...

1300
00:43:02,842 --> 00:43:04,612
when you drink.

1301
00:43:05,112 --> 00:43:06,681
I think I really liked the sound...

1302
00:43:06,682 --> 00:43:08,881
- of liquor fermenting in a jar.
- There's a sound?

1303
00:43:08,882 --> 00:43:10,721
So I learned about liquor.

1304
00:43:10,722 --> 00:43:11,851
I really liked drinking as well.

1305
00:43:11,852 --> 00:43:13,352
When you're an arts major,

1306
00:43:13,452 --> 00:43:16,022
you always drink after everything.

1307
00:43:16,322 --> 00:43:18,092
So I was trained from a young age.

1308
00:43:18,362 --> 00:43:21,891
I used to make and grow makgeolli in my room,

1309
00:43:21,892 --> 00:43:23,332
and turned into a tavern hostess.

1310
00:43:25,932 --> 00:43:28,501
(My own liquor, brewed by my own hands)

1311
00:43:28,502 --> 00:43:30,772
I started my business. I started...

1312
00:43:30,872 --> 00:43:33,741
a traditional Korean liquor bar in Haebangchon,

1313
00:43:33,742 --> 00:43:35,412
- Right.
- and it’s been eight years already.

1314
00:43:35,542 --> 00:43:37,411
- You have to open it quickly.
- I think it was my destiny.

1315
00:43:37,412 --> 00:43:39,241
Liquor came before food for you.

1316
00:43:39,242 --> 00:43:41,411
- I cooked as a hobby.
- You cooked.

1317
00:43:41,412 --> 00:43:43,212
I made it my profession...

1318
00:43:43,452 --> 00:43:45,081
- to make liquor.
- What do you mean...

1319
00:43:45,082 --> 00:43:46,482
you won the Minister's Award for liquor?

1320
00:43:46,622 --> 00:43:48,992
- An award for traditional liquor?
- That's right.

1321
00:43:49,152 --> 00:43:50,591
There's a very famous competition...

1322
00:43:50,592 --> 00:43:53,122
called the Korea Fine Brews Awards.

1323
00:43:53,462 --> 00:43:56,262
I made soju there...

1324
00:43:56,492 --> 00:43:58,332
- and won the Gold Prize.
- What was the alcohol percentage?

1325
00:43:58,562 --> 00:44:01,032
When you make soju, it's around 45 to 50 percent alcohol.

1326
00:44:01,102 --> 00:44:03,701
Do the judges drink it?

1327
00:44:03,702 --> 00:44:06,642
- Yes. Very famous...
- It'd be better if you're the last.

1328
00:44:06,742 --> 00:44:08,512
They would be objective at first, but toward the end...

1329
00:44:10,072 --> 00:44:11,112
- That's a good point.
- That's...

1330
00:44:11,212 --> 00:44:12,881
- That's...
- That's...

1331
00:44:12,882 --> 00:44:14,152
The experts participate in it.

1332
00:44:14,582 --> 00:44:16,081
If it's 45 to 50 percent alcohol...

1333
00:44:16,082 --> 00:44:17,752
My turn was the first.

1334
00:44:17,922 --> 00:44:19,752
- That would have been hard.
- So they would have been sober.

1335
00:44:20,352 --> 00:44:21,492
What do you make soju with?

1336
00:44:21,522 --> 00:44:23,421
Soju is made with makgeolli...

1337
00:44:23,422 --> 00:44:24,891
or by distilling the clear part...

1338
00:44:24,892 --> 00:44:26,391
- on top of the makgeolli.
- Right.

1339
00:44:26,392 --> 00:44:28,031
I normally distill the clear part,

1340
00:44:28,032 --> 00:44:29,462
the cheongju.

1341
00:44:30,392 --> 00:44:31,561
That way, it's clean.

1342
00:44:31,562 --> 00:44:34,771
Is there a traditional liquor you'd like to recommend?

1343
00:44:34,772 --> 00:44:37,371
Tell us quickly. He has to pick a dish to eat now.

1344
00:44:37,372 --> 00:44:39,942
Say I ordered Pyongyang naengmyeon.

1345
00:44:40,172 --> 00:44:42,672
- Pyongyang naengmyeon with bulgogi.
- Okay.

1346
00:44:42,872 --> 00:44:44,611
I won't completely dip it in the broth.

1347
00:44:44,612 --> 00:44:46,242
Quickly head out, Moon Wook.

1348
00:44:46,682 --> 00:44:48,051
Run!

1349
00:44:48,052 --> 00:44:50,512
The warm bulgogi and the cold noodles will mix.

1350
00:44:50,752 --> 00:44:51,951
- I'll enjoy a variety of textures.
- Doesn't that call for soju?

1351
00:44:51,952 --> 00:44:53,352
What's a traditional liquor that would go well with that?

1352
00:44:53,452 --> 00:44:54,521
That would be munbaeju.

1353
00:44:54,522 --> 00:44:56,221
- I know munbaeju.
- I think I've heard of it.

1354
00:44:56,222 --> 00:44:58,291
- Munbaeju.
- It also came from North Korea.

1355
00:44:58,292 --> 00:44:59,962
It has a wild pear aroma too.

1356
00:45:00,162 --> 00:45:01,862
We distil the soju with sorghum.

1357
00:45:01,992 --> 00:45:04,361
So it would go really well with the aroma...

1358
00:45:04,362 --> 00:45:05,431
- of the Pyongyang naengmyeon - Wild pear aroma.

1359
00:45:05,432 --> 00:45:06,531
- and the bulgogi.
- Wild pear.

1360
00:45:06,532 --> 00:45:08,631
- Right. There's no wild pear...
- It has a wild pear aroma?

1361
00:45:08,632 --> 00:45:10,231
- They're hard and small.
- in it, but you can feel the aroma.

1362
00:45:10,232 --> 00:45:11,701
It came from Pyongyang,

1363
00:45:11,702 --> 00:45:13,641
- so I think it would go well.
- Jun Ha knows a lot about alcohol.

1364
00:45:13,642 --> 00:45:15,841
What goes well with raw fish?

1365
00:45:15,842 --> 00:45:18,982
It goes well with the yakju that rises to the top of makgeolli.

1366
00:45:19,442 --> 00:45:21,482
When traditional yeast is used, it’s called yakju.

1367
00:45:21,612 --> 00:45:23,811
The acidity and citrus flavor...

1368
00:45:23,812 --> 00:45:25,481
- go well with it.
- With raw fish.

1369
00:45:25,482 --> 00:45:27,321
I'm curious about the liquor that goes with Chinese food.

1370
00:45:27,322 --> 00:45:30,092
I like ulmyeon, but not many places sell ulmyeon these days.

1371
00:45:30,522 --> 00:45:33,562
Is there a Chinese liquor that goes well with ulmyeon?

1372
00:45:34,192 --> 00:45:36,792
Chinese liquor, out of the blue? She makes Korean liquor.

1373
00:45:37,062 --> 00:45:39,031
- Asking her about Chinese liquor?
- Chinese liquor? Are you asking me?

1374
00:45:39,032 --> 00:45:40,502
- Maotai!
- Chinese liquor...

1375
00:45:41,902 --> 00:45:43,871
- What about...
- Shuijingfang...

1376
00:45:43,872 --> 00:45:46,142
There's Maotai, Kongfujiajiu...

1377
00:45:46,402 --> 00:45:47,671
and Zhuyeqing Chiew.

1378
00:45:47,672 --> 00:45:49,171
- There's a lot of it.
- Maotai.

1379
00:45:49,172 --> 00:45:50,882
- It's cheap as well.
- Just go with Yantai.

1380
00:45:51,042 --> 00:45:53,212
Hoon wrote...

1381
00:45:53,512 --> 00:45:56,882
- "MasterChef Korea's judge."
- That's right.

1382
00:45:57,012 --> 00:45:58,651
I think I saw you...

1383
00:45:58,652 --> 00:46:00,282
- losing your temper there.
- He was very cold.

1384
00:46:00,452 --> 00:46:03,691
"MasterChef Korea" was there...

1385
00:46:03,692 --> 00:46:05,561
before "Culinary Class Wars."

1386
00:46:05,562 --> 00:46:08,231
- That's right.
- There are many versions of it...

1387
00:46:08,232 --> 00:46:09,961
- like the British one.
- That's right.

1388
00:46:09,962 --> 00:46:12,962
It's actually a great honor...

1389
00:46:13,232 --> 00:46:14,471
to be a judge there.

1390
00:46:14,472 --> 00:46:17,442
The rights to that show are owned by the UK.

1391
00:46:17,642 --> 00:46:19,371
The credentials of the judges...

1392
00:46:19,372 --> 00:46:21,071
are sent there for checking.

1393
00:46:21,072 --> 00:46:22,141
Is it that serious?

1394
00:46:22,142 --> 00:46:24,042
- They review and approve you.
- I see.

1395
00:46:24,112 --> 00:46:27,512
At the time, Korea had no Michelin ratings.

1396
00:46:27,712 --> 00:46:30,182
- When I worked in New York, - Right.

1397
00:46:30,412 --> 00:46:32,021
I gained recognition as the sous chef...

1398
00:46:32,022 --> 00:46:34,422
who upgraded a restaurant...

1399
00:46:34,552 --> 00:46:36,252
from 1 Michelin star to 3.

1400
00:46:36,492 --> 00:46:39,422
So I got to be the judge in "MasterChef Korea."

1401
00:46:39,692 --> 00:46:41,631
At what age did you want to start cooking?

1402
00:46:41,632 --> 00:46:45,332
I’ve been interested in cooking since middle school.

1403
00:46:45,532 --> 00:46:47,332
Later, I joined the military,

1404
00:46:47,702 --> 00:46:49,832
and I was an administrative soldier.

1405
00:46:50,302 --> 00:46:53,141
There was a problem with those working at the officers' cafeteria.

1406
00:46:53,142 --> 00:46:54,411
There were two of them,

1407
00:46:54,412 --> 00:46:57,442
but they both happened to go to the military detention.

1408
00:46:57,812 --> 00:47:00,542
I went in their place.

1409
00:47:00,782 --> 00:47:02,081
It was during my final year of service.

1410
00:47:02,082 --> 00:47:03,711
They told me to work there.

1411
00:47:03,712 --> 00:47:07,151
So I made fried rice and soup.

1412
00:47:07,152 --> 00:47:08,522
That was the beginning for me.

1413
00:47:08,922 --> 00:47:11,992
The people there liked it so much.

1414
00:47:12,492 --> 00:47:13,591
Didn't you feel that as well?

1415
00:47:13,592 --> 00:47:14,992
- Right. It was the same.
- You start cooking...

1416
00:47:15,392 --> 00:47:18,531
- when people eating your food...
- When they're happy.

1417
00:47:18,532 --> 00:47:21,201
You never forget that moment when they smile.

1418
00:47:21,202 --> 00:47:23,202
That's how I started cooking.

1419
00:47:23,732 --> 00:47:25,142
- It's romantic.
- I decided to go abroad to study...

1420
00:47:25,302 --> 00:47:27,442
after being discharged from the military.

1421
00:47:28,742 --> 00:47:31,111
You were in a Michelin three-star restaurant.

1422
00:47:31,112 --> 00:47:34,881
Which famous people have been to the restaurant?

1423
00:47:34,882 --> 00:47:37,651
There's a restaurant called Eleven Madison Park in New York,

1424
00:47:37,652 --> 00:47:40,382
and it's a Michelin three-star restaurant.

1425
00:47:40,822 --> 00:47:44,162
But the most important thing is the four-star in the New York Times.

1426
00:47:44,422 --> 00:47:45,692
Such places are seven-star restaurants.

1427
00:47:45,892 --> 00:47:48,362
There aren't that many seven-star restaurants.

1428
00:47:48,832 --> 00:47:49,962
There are about 4 or 5.

1429
00:47:50,292 --> 00:47:51,562
What was unique for us...

1430
00:47:51,962 --> 00:47:54,672
was that there were always two chefs assigned each day.

1431
00:47:54,902 --> 00:47:58,871
They explain the dishes for the day.

1432
00:47:58,872 --> 00:48:01,142
If the chefs explain the dishes,

1433
00:48:01,242 --> 00:48:02,471
it makes the food...

1434
00:48:02,472 --> 00:48:03,671
- very reliable and tastier.
- That's right.

1435
00:48:03,672 --> 00:48:05,581
Then among the people you've explained the dishes to,

1436
00:48:05,582 --> 00:48:06,941
was there Former President Obama?

1437
00:48:06,942 --> 00:48:08,512
Many people visited.

1438
00:48:08,582 --> 00:48:10,612
I remember...

1439
00:48:10,752 --> 00:48:12,982
that many presidents visited the restaurant.

1440
00:48:13,852 --> 00:48:15,692
- Mariah.
- Mariah Carey also came.

1441
00:48:15,822 --> 00:48:19,821
Obama and his wife also came. So many people came.

1442
00:48:19,822 --> 00:48:22,432
The current President also visited.

1443
00:48:22,662 --> 00:48:25,031
He wasn't the President then,

1444
00:48:25,032 --> 00:48:28,372
but he came and spent so much money.

1445
00:48:28,632 --> 00:48:30,371
- Really?
- Even a bottle of wine...

1446
00:48:30,372 --> 00:48:31,471
would be expensive.

1447
00:48:31,472 --> 00:48:33,001
Right. A bottle of wine would cost...

1448
00:48:33,002 --> 00:48:35,571
- 70,000 to 80,000 dollars.
